<page Intro>
<h1>This is a study on Memory.</h1><hr>
You will get several lists of words to study. The words are presented in the middle of the screen, one at a time, at a steady pace.
Pay close attention to each word.<br>
<br>Immediately after the last word, you are asked to do one of these 2 tasks:<br>
<br>(A) Recall Test or (B) Math Test
</page>

<page Intro2>
<h1>(A) Recall Test</h1><hr>
If you are asked to to do the recall test, you will be provided a textbox in the middle of the screen. Type as many words
of the list as you remember. <u>Type each word on a new line.</u><br>
<br>Start with the last few items first and then recall the remaining words in any order.<br>
<br>Write down all the words you remember but be reasonably confident that each word you write down was in fact part of the study list.<br>
<br><br>You will have <%parameters.maxRecallDuration/1000/60%>min to complete the recall task before the next study list will be presented.
</page>

<page Intro3>
<h1>(B) Math Test</h1><hr>
If you are asked to do the math test, you will receive simple addition and multiplication problems. Solve as many as you can.<br>
<br>You will have <%parameters.maxRecallDuration/1000/60%>min to complete the math task before the next study list will be presented.<br>
<br><br>Start with the first study list when you are ready.
</page>

<page recognitionPhase>
<h1>Recognition Test </h1><hr>
You will now receive a second memory test.<br>
<br>In this task you will see a single word and are asked to decide whether the word was part of any of the word lists
you previously studied.<br>
<br>Select <b>OLD</b> if the word was one of the words from your study lists, but select <b>NEW</b> if it was not.
</page>

<page recognitionPhase2>
<h1>Recognition Test </h1><hr>
If you select <b>OLD</b>, you will be asked to distinguish between <i>'REMEMBERING'</i> the item on the study lists and 
simply <i>'KNOWING'</i> it was one of the study lists.<br>
<br>Make a <b>'REMEMBER judgment'</b> when you have a memory of the actual presentation of this word. For example,
you might still remember something distinctive about the speakers voice while presenting this particular word.
Or you might remember what you were thinking when you studied this word.<br>
<br>Make a <b>'KNOW judgment'</b> when you think the item was on one of the lists but you lack an actual 
memory of its presentation.<br>
<br>Always make your choice in regard to its actual presentation, not based on a memory that you
wrote it down during a recall test.
<br><br><br>Start when you are ready.
</page>

<page End>
<center><br><br><br><br>
<h1>Thank You!</h1><br>
You have reached the end of the task.<br>
</page>

<text recallInstructions>
/ items = ("Recall as many of the words from the previous study list as you can.
 Press <Enter> key after each word.")
/ position = (50%, 10%)
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, true, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ size = (90%, 10%)
</text>

<text recognitionInstructions>
/ items = ("Is this word one of your study words (=OLD) or not (=NEW)?")
/ position = (50%, 10%)
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, true, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ size = (80%, 10%)
</text>

<text rememberknowInstructions>
/ items = ("Do you REMEMBER the following word from your study lists or simply KNOW it was on one of the lists?")
/ position = (50%, 10%)
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, true, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ size = (80%, 10%)
</text>

<text break>
